      "writtenOn": "2020-06-22T15:24:34Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "In today\u0027s codebase (with or without my CL), resize() is documented to destroy the string. After calling resize(1234) on a string, fLength will be 1234, and the string contents are frequently empty or garbage.\n\nI\u0027m not sure how to align that with your previous comment :| \n\nresize() mucks up string contents and always has. This CL is intended to make the mucking up more predictable, and give it a name that makes it obvious that mucking-about will occur :)  \n\nI would be equially happy if \"resize\" were a string-preserving resize honestly. What do you think? I could rework this CL into \"resize never destroys user data.\" It might have a trivial performance cost but I can\u0027t imagine it will be measurable in any way. resize() is rarely used anyway, possibly because of it weird semantics.",
      "parentUuid": "4f02ce2a_4f2214f4",
      "revId": "b3833f72eacacc70e8b17afd59c591633869c981",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "5c59eb66_c3afd2fe",
        "filename": "src/core/SkString.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 346,
      "author": {
        "id": 5140
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-06-22T15:34:19Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I suppose what I\u0027m pointing out is that previous callers mostly knew that they were only shortening the string some (usually small, often zero) amount (and logically already had) so they were effectively just modifying fLength without actually doing anything about the existing allocation. More than anything else they were desperately trying to avoid doing allocations or copies just to make the string some tiny amount shorter (often not even changing the length at all).\n\nThe issue I have with this change in particular is that it\u0027s doing more work but \u0027resetToSize\u0027 is still supposed to produce garbage. If it is supposed to produce garbage then there is no need to do this. If it isn\u0027t supposed to produce garbage then it\u0027s wrong.",
      "parentUuid": "5a333dfe_01f43671",
      "revId": "b3833f72eacacc70e8b17afd59c591633869c981",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "db43a7db_a48d6efc",
        "filename": "src/core/SkString.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 346,
      "author": {
        "id": 11059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-06-22T16:09:24Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003c\u003c\nI suppose what I\u0027m pointing out is that previous callers mostly knew that they were only shortening the string some (usually small, often zero) amount (and logically already had) so they were effectively just modifying fLength without actually doing anything about the existing allocation.\n\u003e\u003e\nYeah, unless the string was non-unique and then they were nuking the string :) This is not easy to reason about and can change at a distance. Someone far away from your resize call can pass the SkString to a helper function, creating a short-lived duplicate, and now it\u0027s non-unique and that resize() call behaves differently.\n\nI\u0027m OK with an API guarantee of \"resize can safely shrink strings but trashes them when they grow\" but that\u0027s not what we actually have today--we have a close approximation that is fragile  enough that it can be broken by changes many lines away from the resize call.\n\nBased on this conversation, IMO, I think we should have resize() stay as resize(), but we should remove the string trashing aspect of it. Uniqueness is too dangerous. There are two major use cases and I think neither of them will actually be impacted negatively:\n\n- Growing an empty string to a desired size; this will remain safe and fast. Buffer contents don\u0027t matter and no copy occurs.\n\n- Shrinking an existing buffer and preserving contents; this should be safe and fast. No copy occurs unless the string is non-unique. That case is uncommon and callers don\u0027t defend against it; it\u0027s better to handle this correctly than to be a tiny bit faster.\n\nLess common use cases:\n\n- Growing a populated buffer--this is actually pretty rare from what I\u0027ve seen. Let\u0027s preserve the contents to make the API less surprising. If you want to be fast, you can reset() and then resize().\n\nWhat do you think of this approach?",
      "parentUuid": "5c59eb66_c3afd2fe",
      "revId": "b3833f72eacacc70e8b17afd59c591633869c981",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
