    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "10190d10_c32fda67",
        "filename": "src/ports/SkFontMgr_android_parser.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 147,
      "author": {
        "id": 11059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-06-22T14:54:30Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I can try to make this faster, but the original code was actually treading on very thin ice. From an API guarantee perspective, resize() was documented as a \"destructive resize\" and didn\u0027t promise anything about retaining the buffer contents. If you control the SkString usage carefully, you could work around that by reading the implementation and ensuring that: \n- the SkString keeps its \"unique\" status (never allow the copy-constructor to be invoked)\n- your calls to \"resize\" always shrink the string\n- no one ever changes the implementation of \"resize\"\n\nThis code takes in an SkString from the outside world, which may not necessarily have been unique. The uniqueness state of an SkString is maintained as an implementation detail and can change any time the copy constructor is invoked. If this uniqueness property were lost, this call to `resize` would actually destroy the string and return garbage.\n\nI assume that in practice this was working, but it\u0027s honestly a really good example of why the original resize API was dangerous and why I\u0027m trying to make its behavior easier to reason about.",
      "parentUuid": "3c48f3a7_9818c99f",
      "revId": "b3833f72eacacc70e8b17afd59c591633869c981",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
